One extremely crude but sometimes useful rule of thumb is that a business i=
s worth about 10 times as much as it made this year. If you have a hardware=
 store or a dental practice or a newsletter and it made $1 million this yea=
r, and you want to sell it to someone else, they should pay you about $10 m=
illion for it.
Oh, I=E2=80=99m kidding! Not literally 10!
  [1]
=C2=A0There are tons of variables that go into any valuation, and I am igno=
ring all of them. How fast is the business growing? What do its long-term p=
rospects look like? What do I even mean by =E2=80=9Cmade $1 million=E2=80=
=9D: Is that net income, or revenue, or Ebitda (earnings before interest, t=
axes, depreciation and amortization), or some other measure of earnings? A =
business is worth the value of all of its expected future cash flows, disco=
unted back to present value at some appropriate cost of capital. Sometimes,=
 the growth rate and discount rate will work out such that=C2=A0that number=
 will turn out to be roughly 10 times this year=E2=80=99s earnings, but of =
course it could be much more or much less. Still, I mean, gun to my head, 1=
0.
  [2]

Of course there is not a gun to my head. If someone came to me and said =E2=
=80=9CI have a business that made $1 million this year, would you pay me $1=
0 million for it,=E2=80=9D I would not just hand over the money. I would ha=
ve follow-up questions. One million of net income or revenue or Ebitda or w=
hat? What were the earnings=C2=A0last=C2=A0year? What=E2=80=99s the pipelin=
e look like for next year? Will management be staying on? What does this bu=
siness do? Basic stuff like that. Nobody buys a business by blindly using s=
ome all-purpose multiple of=C2=A0one=C2=A0year=E2=80=99s earnings. They use=
 context to figure out the appropriate multiple for that particular type of=
 business at this moment in the economic cycle, and they adjust their valua=
tion for specific problems or opportunities or one-off events that might ma=
ke this year=E2=80=99s earnings not representative of the business=E2=80=99=
s long-term prospects.
Except Warren Buffett, one time. At the Wall Street Journal, Jonathan Weil =
has a fun story about how Buffett=E2=80=99s Berkshire Hathaway Inc. agreed =
in 2017 to buy a truck-stop chain called Pilot Travel Centers for 10 times =
its earnings in 2023. Not=C2=A0quite:=C2=A0What actually happened is that B=
erkshire bought 38.6% of Pilot Travel Centers in 2017 for 10 times its EBIT=
 (earnings before interest and taxes)=C2=A0that=C2=A0year, but also agreed,=
 at the same time, to buy another 41.4% in January 2023, and to buy the rem=
aining 20% in January 2024, each time using the same formula, that is, 10 t=
imes the previous year=E2=80=99s EBIT.
  [3]
=C2=A0The first two purchases have closed, so Berkshire now owns 80% of Pil=
ot Travel Centers; the other 20% is owned by =E2=80=9Ctruck-stop mogul=C2=
=A0Jimmy Haslam,=E2=80=9D the son of Pilot=E2=80=99s founder. And soon Berk=
shire will have to buy the other 20% of Pilot Travel Centers from Haslam fo=
r 10 times its 2023 earnings. Whatever they are.
This creates incentives for gamesmanship! Specifically:
=09If you are Haslam, your incentives are to make the 2023 earnings as high=
 as possible, so you can get paid 10 times a large number.=09If you are Ber=
kshire Hathaway, your incentives are to make the 2023 earnings as low as po=
ssible, so you can pay 10 times a small number.

Ordinarily, in situations vaguely similar to this, only one side has an=C2=
=A0opportunity=C2=A0for gamesmanship. Usually it=E2=80=99s the seller. Usua=
lly it is like, you run a company, you want to sell some or all of it (in a=
n initial public offering, to a strategic buyer, to a venture investor, wha=
tever), you know that the buyer will slap some multiple on this year=E2=80=
=99s earnings, so you try to gussy up this year=E2=80=99s earnings. Weil qu=
otes law professor Jordan Barry:

Barry gave a hypothetical example of how getting paid based on a multiple o=
f 10 times EBIT could incentivize a company being bought to accept lower pr=
ices on contracts just to get them booked in the current year.
=E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s say this contract would make you $100,000 normally, =
but you close this year if you=E2=80=99re willing to do it at $80,000,=E2=
=80=9D Barry said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s not usually a great trade. You j=
ust lost $20,000.=E2=80=9D
But, because the company is being sold, that contract is then worth $800,00=
0. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s a great trade for you,=E2=80=9D he said.

That=E2=80=99s why buyers are skeptical, and ask questions about the=C2=A0q=
uality=C2=A0of this year=E2=80=99s earnings before just paying 10 times EBI=
T. But of course if you have already agreed in advance to pay 10 times EBIT=
, you don=E2=80=99t get to ask those questions.
Here, though, both sides allegedly have an opportunity for gamesmanship: Be=
rkshire, the buyer, already owns 80% of Pilot Travel Centers, so it control=
s the board and appoints the chief executive officer, who can probably do t=
hings to make this year=E2=80=99s earnings lower. But Haslam, the seller, i=
s the founder; he has closer connections to the company=E2=80=99s managers,=
 and can call them up and ask them to juice this year=E2=80=99s earnings.
And so Haslam=E2=80=99s company, Pilot Corp.,=C2=A0sued Berkshire, arguing =
that it is artificially depressing earnings to lower its purchase price, an=
d Berkshire countersued Pilot, arguing that Haslam is artificially inflatin=
g earnings to increase his sale price. Haslam=E2=80=99s argument is about a=
ccounting: When Berkshire took over Pilot Travel Centers earlier this year,=
 it changed the company=E2=80=99s accounting policies in a way that did not=
 change its=C2=A0economics, but did decrease its=C2=A0accounting earnings. =
Weil:

The argument centers on a financial-reporting method known as pushdown acco=
unting. When a company gets bought, it can choose whether to revalue all th=
e assets and liabilities on its own separate set of books, in effect =E2=80=
=9Cpushing down=E2=80=9D the acquirer=E2=80=99s purchase price and using th=
at as the basis for the new values. The method is optional. Companies have =
wide discretion on whether to apply it. But if they do, the decision is irr=
evocable.
If a company wants to show lower profits over the short term after getting =
acquired, it can write up its asset values so it will show higher expenses =
for things like depreciation and amortization. Pilot Corp. said Berkshire d=
id this with PTC=E2=80=99s financial statements, which are separate from Be=
rkshire=E2=80=99s, along with other adjustments that cut PTC=E2=80=99s earn=
ings.

Meanwhile Berkshire argues that Haslam secretly bribed the managers to juic=
e profits. From its=C2=A0counterclaim:

In early November 2023, during a routine meeting with PTC=E2=80=99s current=
