In theory, every time one company does a merger with another company, or a=
=C2=A0private equity firm raises a fund from investors, or a private equity=
 fund borrows money from lenders to do a leveraged buyout, the two sides co=
uld negotiate all the details of the merger or fund or loan from scratch. S=
it down and think through the deal from first principles: What rights shoul=
d each side have? Who should have to do what? What could go wrong, and who =
should bear the risk of each thing that could go wrong? Negotiate each of t=
hese points, and then write a contract in elegant prose that reflects your =
negotiation.
This never really happens.
  [4]
=C2=A0Instead the way it works is that the lawyers for one side take out th=
e contract that they wrote for the last similar deal that they did, and the=
y change the names, and they tweak a few provisions to reflect the current =
situation, and they tweak a few more provisions to be=C2=A0more aggressive=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to give their client more rights or fewer responsibili=
ties, to allocate more risks to the other side =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then they=
 send it to the other side. And the lawyers for the other side mark up the =
contract to make it more favorable to them (more rights, fewer responsibili=
ties, less risk), and also to make it look more like the last contract=C2=
=A0they=C2=A0wrote, and they send it back, and they negotiate from there.=
=C2=A0
In those negotiations, the two sides can make several types of arguments. F=
or instance:
=09Some provisions are win-win, so you can say =E2=80=9Cif you agree to thi=
s it will be better for both of us.=E2=80=9D=09Some provisions are just int=
uitively fair, so you can say =E2=80=9Cit makes no sense for you to allocat=
e this risk to us, this is a risk that you should bear,=E2=80=9D and convin=
ce the other side of it. (Or: =E2=80=9CIf the contract says this, then that=
 would allow you to do this crazy unfair thing, and obviously you would nev=
er want to do that, so we should change the contract to constrain you in a =
fair way.=E2=80=9D)=09Sometimes one side has more negotiating leverage, so =
it can just say =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t agree to this we will walk,=
=E2=80=9D and the other side has to agree.=09There=E2=80=99s a certain amou=
nt of arbitrary horse-trading and wearing down of the other side: At 3 a.m.=
, one side says =E2=80=9Cfine you can have these six points if you give me =
those other four points,=E2=80=9D and the other side is like =E2=80=9Cfine =
whatever let=E2=80=99s be done.=E2=80=9D

But for many terms in the contract, the=C2=A0main=C2=A0argument will be: =
=E2=80=9CThis term is market.=E2=80=9D
  [5]
 =E2=80=9CMarket=E2=80=9D means that it is the normal way that these sorts =
of deals are done by sophisticated parties with sophisticated lawyers. =E2=
=80=9CMarket=E2=80=9D is a sort of efficient-market=C2=A0argument. It means=
 =E2=80=9Ca lot of smart people have argued over this term from first princ=
iples, they have thought about what is fair and what is in everyone=E2=80=
=99s best interests, and their collective conclusion is that the provision =
should be written this way. So who are you to argue for something different=
?=E2=80=9D If there have been 50 private equity leveraged buyouts in the la=
st three years, and 48 of them had a   cap on damages for non-performance, =
then that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cmarket=E2=80=9D and it is hard =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
not impossible, but hard =E2=80=94=C2=A0for the target to argue that there =
should be no damages cap.
How do you know what is market? Well, you look at all the previous deals, o=
r as many as you can. Sometimes this is reasonably easy: In the US, the ter=
ms of some types of deals (public company mergers, initial public offerings=
, some bond deals) are publicly disclosed with the US Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission, so you can just go find them all. (Or all the big ones, or a=
ll the ones in your industry, or whatever the relevant market is. And obvio=
usly you focus on the recent=C2=A0ones, since the market evolves.) You have=
 to pay attention to what deals happen, and have someone summarize them, bu=
t with a bit of work you can build a database, or even keep running track o=
f all the deals in your head I guess.
  [6]
=C2=A0Or get yourself a large language model and ask it =E2=80=9Cwhat is a =
standard   ordinary course of business covenant for a US public company mer=
ger these days?=E2=80=9D
Other times it is hard: Many deals are=C2=A0not=C2=A0publicly disclosed, an=
d if you want to know what the standard terms are for, say, the limited par=
tnership agreement of a new private equity fund, the best way to do that is=
 to have negotiated a ton of private equity fund agreements. If you=E2=80=
=99ve done all of those deals, then you have a database (or all the deal te=
rms in your head), and if the people on the other side haven=E2=80=99t done=
 the deals, then they don=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
And so you can say =E2=80=9Cthis term is market=E2=80=9D and they can say =
=E2=80=9Cno it isn=E2=80=99t=E2=80=9D and you can say =E2=80=9CI have negot=
iated 100 of these deals and this term is in every one of them, how many ha=
ve you negotiated,=E2=80=9D and they will say =E2=80=9Cum, four,=E2=80=9D a=
nd they will be ashamed in front of their clients. You will look wise and e=
xperienced, and they will look dumb and unreasonable. And you will win the =
argument. Not always or anything =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s not like anyon=
e is obligated to agree to =E2=80=9Cmarket=E2=80=9D terms =E2=80=94=C2=A0bu=
t it=E2=80=99s a fairly effective move.
Also though if you say =E2=80=9CI have negotiated 100 of these deals and th=
is term is in every one of them,=E2=80=9D and they haven=E2=80=99t, and the=
 deals aren=E2=80=99t public, they can=E2=80=99t check. If you negotiate al=
l the deals, you can=C2=A0change=C2=A0what terms are market.=C2=A0
At the Financial Times, Will Louch has a fascinating  profile of Kirkland &=
 Ellis, a US law firm that has become influential and lucrative by building=
 a strong private equity practice and by being more aggressive and commerci=
al than other law firms. There is a lot about the culture and business mode=
l of Kirkland, for instance:

Unlike other, stuffier firms, if you are good enough you rise through the r=
anks fast rather than waiting for existing partners to retire or die, he ad=
ds. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s run like a business and not like a club. A lot of=
 law firms are run like clubs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Another longtime partner says the promotion prospects are =E2=80=9Cone of t=
he unique things about Kirkland=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89you d=
on=E2=80=99t have to wait until you are 60. You can be rewarded really earl=
y on and it can give you a sense of energy.=E2=80=9D

But also, because Kirkland=E2=80=99s private equity practices are so big, t=
hey have the ability to move what is market:

Investors and trade associations are also taking a closer look at Kirkland=
=E2=80=99s modus operandi. Because it works on so many deals =E2=80=94 it h=
as advised on more fundraisings than any other firm in every year since 200=
8, according to data provider Preqin =E2=80=94 it collects reams of data ab=
out fees and other terms. The firm invested heavily in using this data to i=
ts advantage, even hiring data scientists from the University of Chicago to=
 track deal terms.
It uses this data to get better terms for its own clients, making life diff=
icult for less well-resourced investors such as public pension plans. =E2=
=80=9CThey have the largest market share,=E2=80=9D says the head of private=
 equity at a large US public pension plan. =E2=80=9CThey will pick a few te=
rms each year and insist they are [the] market=E2=80=9D,
  [7]
 rolling them out across most of the private equity funds they advise.
=E2=80=9CIt is one of our selling points,=E2=80=9D a person familiar with t=
he firm=E2=80=99s workings says. =E2=80=9COur market knowledge is better th=
an our competitors.=E2=80=9D
The concentration of market share in the hands of a few large firms, includ=
ing Simpson Thacher and Proskauer, has attracted criticism from the Institu=
tional Limited Partners Association, a Washington-based industry body repre=
senting private equity investors. In a report earlier this year, it highlig=
hted the role that lawyers play in helping fund managers negotiate better t=
erms at the expense of investors.
Investors say they are accused of collusion if they try to band together wi=
th peers to get better terms, with Kirkland among the most aggressive law f=
irms at rebutting any pushback.

One other way to influence what is =E2=80=9Cmarket=E2=80=9D=C2=A0is=C2=A0to=
 band together with peers, say by being the Institutional Limited Partners =
Association and publishing your own  model private equity fund agreement. =
=E2=80=9CThis term is in the model agreement so it must be right=E2=80=9D i=
s not quite the same sort of argument as =E2=80=9Cthis term is market so it=
 must be right,=E2=80=9D but it has some appeal.

