An odd institutional dynamic in US regulation right now is:
=09The regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0at the Federal Trade Commission and the Se=
curities and Exchange Commission, at least =E2=80=94=C2=A0are unusually agg=
ressive about asserting and expanding their power to regulate.=09The courts=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in particular the US Supreme Court =E2=80=94=C2=A0are u=
nusually skeptical of regulation and willing to cut back the power of regul=
ators.

I guess that just means =E2=80=9Cthe president is a Democrat and the Suprem=
e Court are mostly Republicans=E2=80=9D? Anyway we have   talked a few   ti=
mes about how the SEC=E2=80=99s aggressiveness about expanding its power ha=
s clashed with courts that are increasingly aggressive about limiting its p=
ower. And here is a  New York Magazine story about Lina Khan, the chair of =
the FTC, who has tried to expand the possibilities for US antitrust law=C2=
=A0and has had a string of losses:

A bleaker scenario posited by others is that Khan=E2=80=99s tenure at the a=
gency could end up playing into the hands of a skeptical Supreme Court, who=
se conservative majority has made clear that it will push back on what it b=
elieves =E2=80=94 fairly or not =E2=80=94 to constitute overreach on the pa=
rt of the executive branch. [Former FTC Chair William] Kovacic praised Khan=
 for =E2=80=9Cenergizing a new generation of scholars and students=E2=80=9D=
 but noted that =E2=80=9Cthe federal courts seem to be edging in the direct=
ion of rethinking the scope of the FTC=E2=80=99s power =E2=80=94 its decisi=
on-making framework, the very constitutionality of how it operates.=E2=80=
=9D
The concern is hardly misplaced. The past few years have generated several =
Supreme Court decisions that have curtailed the powers of federal regulator=
s =E2=80=94 including the FTC itself =E2=80=94 and made them more vulnerabl=
e to legal challenges. The justices recently heard oral argument on a legal=
 challenge to the Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s system of in=
-house courts that could also make matters worse for the FTC, which has a s=
imilar system.
=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know how much the commission is thinking at the mo=
ment about the impact of trying to build a more expansive program in the fa=
ce of this gathering judicial storm,=E2=80=9D Kovacic wondered. =E2=80=9CDo=
 you realize you could come out of this with a much-diminished agency?=E2=
=80=9D he asked. =E2=80=9CAnd Congress is not coming to the rescue for you.=
 You could come out of this with an agency that is much weaker than the one=
 that you went in with =E2=80=94 permanently weaker.=E2=80=9D

An FTC that just did traditional FTC stuff might still be constrained by co=
urts that are skeptical of regulation, but an FTC that tries to expand the =
possibilities of FTC regulation might end up significantly limiting it.

