<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Pilot</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One extremely crude but sometimes useful rule =
of thumb is that a business is worth about 10 times as much as it made this=
 year. If you have a hardware store or a dental practice or a newsletter an=
d it made $1 million this year, and you want to sell it to someone else, th=
ey should pay you about $10 million for it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, I=E2=80=99m kidding! Not literally 10!<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There are tons of variables that go into any valuation, and I am =
ignoring all of them. How fast is the business growing? What do its long-te=
rm prospects look like? What do I even mean by =E2=80=9Cmade $1 million=E2=
=80=9D: Is that net income, or revenue, or Ebitda (earnings before interest=
, taxes, depreciation and amortization), or some other measure of earnings?=
 A business is worth the value of all of its expected future cash flows, di=
scounted back to present value at some appropriate cost of capital. Sometim=
es, the growth rate and discount rate will work out such that=C2=A0that num=
ber will turn out to be roughly 10 times this year=E2=80=99s earnings, but =
of course it could be much more or much less. Still, I mean, gun to my head=
, 10.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course there is not a gun to my head. If so=
meone came to me and said =E2=80=9CI have a business that made $1 million t=
his year, would you pay me $10 million for it,=E2=80=9D I would not just ha=
nd over the money. I would have follow-up questions. One million of net inc=
ome or revenue or Ebitda or what? What were the earnings=C2=A0<em>last=C2=
=A0</em>year? What=E2=80=99s the pipeline look like for next year? Will man=
agement be staying on? What does this business <em>do</em>? Basic stuff lik=
e that. Nobody buys a business by blindly using some all-purpose multiple o=
f=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>year=E2=80=99s earnings. They use context to figur=
e out the appropriate multiple for that particular type of business at this=
 moment in the economic cycle, and they adjust their valuation for specific=
 problems or opportunities or one-off events that might make this year=E2=
=80=99s earnings not representative of the business=E2=80=99s long-term pro=
spects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except Warren Buffett, one time. At the Wall S=
treet Journal, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/336=
70492.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy93YXJyZW4tYnVmZmV0dC1iZX=
Jrc2hpcmUtaGF0aGF3YXktamltbXktaGFzbGFtLXBpbG90LWxhd3N1aXQtNzBlZjA0MTM_bW9kP=
WhwX2xlYWRfcG9zOA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBec37a9e3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Jonathan Weil =
has a fun story</a> about how Buffett=E2=80=99s Berkshire Hathaway Inc. agr=
eed in 2017 to buy a truck-stop chain called Pilot Travel Centers for 10 ti=
mes its earnings in 2023. Not=C2=A0<em>quite:=C2=A0</em>What actually happe=
ned is that Berkshire bought 38.6% of Pilot Travel Centers in 2017 for 10 t=
imes its EBIT (earnings before interest and taxes)=C2=A0that=C2=A0year, but=
 also agreed, at the same time, to buy another 41.4% in January 2023, and t=
o buy the remaining 20% in January 2024, each time using the same formula, =
that is, 10 times the previous year=E2=80=99s EBIT.<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The first two purchases have closed, so Berkshire now owns 80% of=
 Pilot Travel Centers; the other 20% is owned by =E2=80=9Ctruck-stop mogul=
=C2=A0Jimmy Haslam,=E2=80=9D the son of Pilot=E2=80=99s founder. And soon B=
erkshire will have to buy the other 20% of Pilot Travel Centers from Haslam=
 for 10 times its 2023 earnings. Whatever they are.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This creates incentives for gamesmanship! Spec=
ifically:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are Haslam, your incentives ar=
e to make the 2023 earnings as high as possible, so you can get paid 10 tim=
es a large number.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are Berk=
shire Hathaway, your incentives are to make the 2023 earnings as low as pos=
sible, so you can pay 10 times a small number.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ordinarily, in situations vaguely similar to t=
his, only one side has an=C2=A0<em>opportunity=C2=A0</em>for gamesmanship. =
Usually it=E2=80=99s the seller. Usually it is like, you run a company, you=
 want to sell some or all of it (in an initial public offering, to a strate=
gic buyer, to a venture investor, whatever), you know that the buyer will s=
lap some multiple on this year=E2=80=99s earnings, so you try to gussy up t=
his year=E2=80=99s earnings. Weil quotes law professor Jordan Barry:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Barry gave a hypothetical example of how getti=
ng paid based on a multiple of 10 times EBIT could incentivize a company be=
ing bought to accept lower prices on contracts just to get them booked in t=
he current year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s say this contract would=
 make you $100,000 normally, but you close this year if you=E2=80=99re will=
ing to do it at $80,000,=E2=80=9D Barry said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s not u=
sually a great trade. You just lost $20,000.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, because the company is being sold, that c=
ontract is then worth $800,000. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s a great trade for y=
ou,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s why buyers are skeptical, and a=
sk questions about the=C2=A0<em>quality=C2=A0</em>of this year=E2=80=99s ea=
rnings before just paying 10 times EBIT. But of course if you have already =
agreed in advance to pay 10 times EBIT, you don=E2=80=99t get to ask those =
questions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, though, both sides allegedly have an opp=
ortunity for gamesmanship: Berkshire, the buyer, already owns 80% of Pilot =
Travel Centers, so it controls the board and appoints the chief executive o=
fficer, who can probably do things to make this year=E2=80=99s earnings low=
er. But Haslam, the seller, is the founder; he has closer connections to th=
e company=E2=80=99s managers, and can call them up and ask them to juice th=
is year=E2=80=99s earnings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so Haslam=E2=80=99s company, Pilot Corp.,=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33670492.258=
399/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J=
0T1RlRjdvTVo0by92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB443a5bad" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sued Berkshi=
re</a>, arguing that it is artificially depressing earnings to lower its pu=
rchase price, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
33670492.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0h=
CRmRmeElVL3JYV2lsNFg1Wk5ray92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4dcd0948" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Berkshire countersued Pilot</a>, arguing that Haslam is artificially inflat=
ing earnings to increase his sale price. Haslam=E2=80=99s argument is about=
 accounting: When Berkshire took over Pilot Travel Centers earlier this yea=
r, it changed the company=E2=80=99s accounting policies in a way that did n=
ot change its=C2=A0<em>economics</em>, but did decrease its=C2=A0<em>accoun=
ting earnings. </em>Weil:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument centers on a financial-reporting =
method known as pushdown accounting. When a company gets bought, it can cho=
ose whether to revalue all the assets and liabilities on its own separate s=
et of books, in effect =E2=80=9Cpushing down=E2=80=9D the acquirer=E2=80=99=
s purchase price and using that as the basis for the new values. The method=
 is optional. Companies have wide discretion on whether to apply it. But if=
 they do, the decision is irrevocable.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a company wants to show lower profits over =
the short term after getting acquired, it can write up its asset values so =
it will show higher expenses for things like depreciation and amortization.=
 Pilot Corp. said Berkshire did this with PTC=E2=80=99s financial statement=
s, which are separate from Berkshire=E2=80=99s, along with other adjustment=
s that cut PTC=E2=80=99s earnings.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile Berkshire argues that Haslam secretl=
y bribed the managers to juice profits. From its=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33670492.258399/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYnd=
ieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JYV2lsNFg1Wk5ray92MA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cC4dcd0948" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">counterclaim</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In early November 2023, during a routine meeti=
ng with PTC=E2=80=99s current CEO Adam Wright, one of PTC=E2=80=99s most se=
nior executives made a shocking disclosure: =E2=80=9CI know there is a narr=
ative out there that I have a side deal with Jimmy [Haslam].=E2=80=9D The e=
xecutive disclosed that Haslam offered to pay him additional compensation, =
outside of PTC=E2=80=99s compensation structure, based on the price Haslam =
expected Pilot to receive if it exercised its Put Option in 2024. The first=
 such overture came during a dinner that Haslam held for PTC executives in =
March 2023.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[At the dinner,] Haslam said that, assuming Pi=
lot exercised its Put Option in 2024, he would reward the assembled executi=
ves with large, one-time bonuses. Specifically, Haslam said that he would r=
eward them in the same manner that they had been rewarded upon the 2023 Sal=
e pursuant to PTC=E2=80=99s then-existing bonus program, known as the Growt=
h Partners Plan (=E2=80=9CGPP=E2=80=9D). ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most, if not all, of the executives who attend=
ed the Cherokee dinner had received Special Distribution awards under the G=
PP=E2=80=94meaning that everyone in the room either already had received, o=
r was about to receive, a very large check personally funded by the Haslam =
family. In many cases, those payments were an order of magnitude greater th=
an the executives=E2=80=99 annual salaries. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Haslam sought only to incentivize executive=
s to remain at PTC, his company Pilot already had an above-board means of d=
oing so. If Haslam thought that the existing, official incentives were not =
enough, he could have recommended that PTC consider more. Instead, during 2=
023, Haslam=E2=80=99s promises would buy something different: the executive=
s=E2=80=99 loyalty to him personally, at the expense of PTC. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Haslam=E2=80=99s illicit promise of secret bon=
uses thereby distorted PTC executives=E2=80=99 financial interests to be al=
igned not with PTC=E2=80=99s interests, but with those of a minority owner =
anticipating selling its remaining stake. Higher EBIT for PTC in 2023 would=
 mean a higher amount paid to Pilot if it exercised the Put Option in 2024,=
 and therefore higher illicit bonuses paid by Jimmy Haslam to PTC=E2=80=99s=
 executives.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The counterclaim then goes on to claim that in=
 fact the executives=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>try to juice the 2023 EBIT:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even before he heard from the two =
senior executives in November 2023, PTC=E2=80=99s current CEO Adam Wright h=
ad been concerned about what appeared to be divided loyalties among PTC=E2=
=80=99s employees. On the business side, he noticed an unwarranted urgency =
among certain employees to close deals in 2023.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The counterclaim seems to have some examples, =
though the details are redacted. But:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although Wright and others noticed and address=
ed these suspicious short-term earnings strategies before they could be car=
ried out, the nature of PTC=E2=80=99s business is such that Wright was not =
in a position to police the huge number of transactions that could have bee=
n influenced by Haslam=E2=80=99s improper promise of under-the-table compen=
sation. In many cases, [<em>redacted</em>] have the authority to enter into=
 transactions that have the effect of either pulling gains forward into a p=
articular earnings period or delaying those gains to a later period. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On information and belief, Haslam=E2=80=99s pr=
omised under-the-table bonuses to PTC=E2=80=99s employees affected their ev=
eryday decision-making in ways large and small, and in ways that PTC could =
not police and cannot now effectively reconstruct. Haslam=E2=80=99s illegit=
imate scheme improperly incentivized key employees to make short-term decis=
ions to the detriment of PTC=E2=80=99s long-term growth and value.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What you want is a price mechanism that is lik=
e =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll pay 10 times EBIT, but we will back out the effect=
s of (1) accounting changes that Berkshire makes and (2) short-term earning=
s shenanigans that management does.=E2=80=9D But it is hard to anticipate a=
nd write all of that. Just writing =E2=80=9C10 times EBIT=E2=80=9D is faste=
r, but it can land you in court.</p>
